Laos , officially known as the Lao People’s Democratic Republic , is a landlocked country in Southeast Asia. The majority of the country is traversed by the mighty Mekong River, which travels through rugged mountains and dense forests. The high biodiversity of the Greater Mekong region has resulted in the discovery of more than 3,000 new species over the past two decades, including numerous endemic species found nowhere else (
). In the past few years, the number of millipede species in Laos has rapidly and consistently increased. Since the most recent catalogue of the Diplopoda of Laos in 2014, which listed 34 species (
), another 49 new species of millipedes have been discovered (
;
;
,
; Golovatch

& VandenSpiegel, 2017; 

; 

; 

; 

). Evidently, there are numerous undiscovered millipede species in the country, eagerly anticipating our perseverance to discover them.

DNA extraction, PCR amplification and sequencing
DNA barcoding (

) was conducted in order to establish species boundaries, and investigate intra- and interspecific barcode distances among the species described here. The DNA extraction, amplification, and sequencing of the cytochrome c oxidase subunit I gene (COI) was done following protocols employed in earlier studies (

; 

), using the degenerate primer pair of the forward primer HCO-JJ (5′-AWA CTT CVG GRT GVC CAA ARA ATC A-3′) and the reverse primer LCO-JJ (5′-CHA CWA AYC 
ATA AAG ATA
TYG G-3′) (

). Sequences were assembled, aligned and edited in BioEdit (

) or utilising the software Seqman (DNASTAR Inc.). BLAST searches (

) were performed to confirm sequence identities and to check for any contamination. The whole dataset was translated into amino acids to rule-out the accidental amplification of pseudogenes. Eleven new sequences from six cambalid millipede species were successfully obtained and have been uploaded to GenBank under the accession codes OR359752–OR359762 (
Table 1
). PCR amplification was unsuccessful for one troglobiotic species, 

Glyphiulus houaphanhensis

, 
new species
, despite several attempts.

In order to get insights on the species delineation pattern of the 
Cambalopsidae
, a p-distance analysis was conducted on the 37 COI sequences. The number of base differences per site between sequences was calculated (see 
Table 2
). Codon positions included were 1st+2nd+3rd. All ambiguous positions were removed for each sequence pair. The p-distance analysis was conducted in MEGA6 (

).

In order to get an overview about the phylogenetic relationships of the newly described and sequenced species among the Cambalopsidae , a maximum likelihood analysis was conducted based on the same COI dataset. Phylogenetic analyses were also performed in MEGA6. The best fitting substitution model for a maximum likelihood analysis was calculated with Modeltest (
) as implemented in MEGA6. The best fitting model was the general time reversible (GTR)-Model (
) with gamma distribution and invariant sites (GTR+G+I) (lnL = -8801.615, Invariant = 0.430 1692, Gamma = 0.654 062057, R = 4.456556; Freq A: 0.292 9, T : 0.335 5, C: 0.216 6, G: 0.1547).

